    "statements": [
        {
            "id": 0,
            "text": "Watts and Strogatz introduced a random rewiring procedure parameterized by p to interpolate between regular and random networks."
        },
        {
            "id": 1,
            "text": "Small-world networks exhibit high clustering like regular lattices yet have short characteristic path lengths like random graphs."
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "text": "Empirical networks—namely the film actors collaboration graph, the US power grid, and the C. elegans neural network—display small-world properties."
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "text": "The characteristic path length L(p) drops rapidly with small p due to the addition of short cuts, while C(p) remains almost unchanged."
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "text": "In a simple infectious-disease model on small-world networks, the critical infectiousness r½ decreases with p and the global infection time T(p) mirrors the behavior of L(p)."
        }
    ],
